				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sum _{v \in C_{i}} deg(v|C_{i}) = 2 (z-1)$\end{document}∑v∈Cideg(v|Ci)=2(z−1). _

INDUCTION HYPOTHESIS. We assume there exists a node ui for all components of size q nodes that can be swapped without disconnecting its component. We consider two cases of one component Ci where vi is connected to through uj. The first case is when Ci contains at least one cycle with the set of nodes, Vc1={v1,v2,…,vn}. It follows that for each node ui∈Vc1 and ui≠uj, ui can be swapped with vi without disconnecting Ci. In the second case, Ci represents acyclic network with no cycles. Next, we prove our theorem in this case by contradiction. First, we assume that the number of nodes in Ci with degree equal to 1 is less than 2. Consequently, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sum _{v \in C_{i}} deg(v|C_{i}) \geq 2 (z-1) + 1$\end{document}∑v∈Cideg(v|Ci)≥2(z−1)+1, which contradicts Lemma 1. Thus, the number of nodes in Ci with degree equal to 1 is at least 2 nodes and thus, ∃v,w∈C st. deg(v|C) = 1 and deg(w|C) = 1 and v≠w. Therefore, we can swap vi with either v or w. __

Next, we prove that swapping a gap node vi with an aligned node ui at each iteration will increase the alignment score \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$score(\mathcal {G}^{1}, \mathcal {G}^{2} | \psi)$\end{document}score(G1,G2|ψ), showing that the alignment score will always improve by our dynamic programming algorithm.

Given a value of δ where δ is greater than or equal to S(ψ(ui), ui) for all ui∈V2. At each iteration of our algorithm, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$score(\mathcal {G}^{1}, \mathcal {G}^{2} | \psi)$\end{document}score(G1,G2|ψ) monotonically increases.

We assume that our algorithm chooses one pair of nodes to swap; a gap node vi and aligned node ui which will connect x number of components. We note that the condition x ≥2 must be satisfied for vi to be considered for swapping. Also, it follows from Lemma 2 that if we swap vi and ui then the number of connected components will not increase. Thus, the difference in the score equals D=δ(x−1)−puv where puv is the difference in pairwise score from swapping (i.e. puv = S(ψ(ui), ui) - S(ψ(ui), vi)). Since δ is greater than or equal to S(u,v)∀u∈V1 and ∈V2, then δ(x−1)≥puv. Consequently, D ≥ 0 and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$score(\mathcal {G}^{1}, \mathcal {G}^{2} | \psi)$\end{document}score(G1,G2|ψ) will not decrease. __

Proof of NP-hardness. Here, we prove that our problem is NP-hard. To do that, we reduce the Maximum Coverage Problem (MCP), which is known to be NP-hard [37], to our problem. Given a positive integer \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\acute {k}$\end{document}k´ and a collection of sets, S={S1,S2,…,Sm}, MCP seeks the subset \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\acute {S} \subseteq $\end{document}Ś⊆S such that \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$|\acute {S}| \leq \acute {k}$\end{document}|Ś|≤k´ and the number of covered elements \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
